  "text": "The regulation of biosurfactant synthesis in P. aeruginosa has proved puzzling [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] because it deviates from the established paradigm of quorum sensing where gene expression is simply a function of cell density. Our study helps to resolve this puzzle by showing that rhlAB expression in the presence of excess carbon can be tightly coupled to the growth rate, and not just cell density (Fig. 6B) . Accordingly, the WT does not secrete biosurfactants, or swarm, unless both quorum-sensing and nutrient conditions are suitable. This suggests that P. aeruginosa has evolved to ensure biosurfactants are only secreted when both cell density is high enough for these secretions to be useful and there is an excess of carbon to minimize the impact of their synthesis (Fig. 9B) .",
